'''''Amanita virgineoides''''', known as the False Virgin's Lepidella, is a [[species]] of the [[genus]] [[Amanita]].

== Description ==

The [[basidiocarp]]s are medium-sized to large. The [[Pileus (mycology)|pileus]] of the cap is 70 - 150 (7 – 15&nbsp;cm) mm wide, is [[Convex geometry|convex]] to applanate, sometimes concave, white, covered with white, [[conical]] to pyramid [[Volva (mycology)|volval]] remnants 1 – 3&nbsp;mm high and wide; the cap margin is smooth and appendiculate; and the context is white and unchanging.<ref name=Amanitaceae>{{cite web | url = http://www.amanitaceae.org/?Amanita+virgineoides | title = ''Amanita virgineoides''|work=Amanitaceae.org |accessdate=October 5, 2016}}</ref>

The [[Gill (mycology)|gills]] are free to subfree and white to cream; the short gills are [[attenuate]].

The [[Stipe (mycology)|stipe]] is 100 - 200 (10 – 20&nbsp;cm) × 15 – 30&nbsp;mm (1.5 – 3&nbsp;cm), [[Cylinder (geometry)|subcylindric]] or slightly attenuate upwards, white, covered with white floccose squamules; the context is white; the stipe's basal bulb is 30 – 40&nbsp;mm wide, [[ventricose]], [[ovoid]] to [[Globose|subglobose]], with its upper part covered with white, [[verrucose]] to granular [[Volva (mycology)|volval]] remnants.  The [[Annulus (mycology)|annulus]] is white; its upper surface bears fine, radial striations; and its lower surface, verrucose to [[conical]] warts.  The annulus is often broken during expansion of the cap.

The spores measure 8.0 - 10.0 (0.8 – 1&nbsp;mm) ×  6.0 - 7.5 (0.6 - 0.75&nbsp;mm) µm and are broadly [[ellipsoid]] to ellipsoid and [[amyloid]].  Clamps are common at bases of [[basidia]].

